# Cloudflare Pages Cache-Control policy for the static export.
# https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/headers/
#
# Without this file the site relies on the host's default caching, which both
# re-fetches content-hashed immutable assets and risks serving stale HTML.
#
# Cloudflare applies *every* matching rule and joins a repeated header with a
# comma, so two rules that both match a path and both set Cache-Control would
# emit one conflicting value. Rules are processed top-to-bottom, and a later,
# more specific rule can detach an inherited header with `! <Header>`. So the
# broad revalidate rule comes first, and each more specific rule below detaches
# that inherited Cache-Control before setting its own — leaving each path with
# a single, unambiguous value instead of several comma-joined ones.

# Baseline security headers, applied site-wide. More specific rules below only
# detach/reset Cache-Control (`! Cache-Control`), so these keep applying to
# every path — including hashed assets and metadata routes — without repeating
# them per rule. No CSP here: the JSON-LD <script> (JsonLdScript.tsx) is inline
# and static-exported with no per-request nonce, so a strict CSP would need
# 'unsafe-inline' anyway; adding one is a separate, larger effort left for later.
#
# - X-Content-Type-Options: stops a browser from MIME-sniffing a response into
#   an executable type against the served Content-Type.
# - Referrer-Policy: sends the full referrer to same-origin requests but only
#   the origin (no path/query) cross-origin, so outbound links don't leak this
#   site's full URL to third parties.
# - X-Frame-Options: DENY — the site never needs to be framed, so refuse
#   clickjacking-style embedding outright.
# - Permissions-Policy: the site doesn't use these browser APIs; disabling
#   them denies a compromised third-party script silent access.
# - Strict-Transport-Security: moadim.io is only ever served over HTTPS (see
#   the www/.pages.dev -> apex redirects in public/_redirects), but without
#   this header a visitor's first request to a bare `http://` link or typed
#   URL still round-trips in plaintext before Cloudflare's edge can apply
#   that redirect, leaving a window for a network attacker to intercept or
#   downgrade it. `max-age=63072000` (2 years) + `includeSubDomains` is the
#   standard baseline (https://hstspreload.org); submitting to the preload
#   list itself is a separate opt-in step, left for later.

# HTML and everything else: cache but always revalidate, so a redeploy is
# picked up immediately instead of serving a stale page.
/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Permissions-Policy: geolocation=(), camera=(), microphone=()
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains

# Next.js emits content-hashed, immutable assets (JS, CSS, fonts, media) under
# /_next/static/*. A new build changes the hash (and the URL), so these can be
# cached forever. Detach the inherited revalidate value from the rule above so
# this path is served with the immutable directive only.
/_next/static/*
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# Generated metadata assets whose referencing URL carries a content hash:
# the OG/Twitter share images (`/opengraph-image?<hash>`, `/twitter-image?<hash>`)
# and the favicon (`/favicon.ico?<hash>`). Because the URL changes whenever the
# bytes change, the bytes at any given URL are immutable — so an unfurl bot or
# crawler can cache them forever instead of re-fetching from the origin on every
# request. Without this they fall under the broad `max-age=0` rule above.
/opengraph-image
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
/twitter-image
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
/favicon.ico
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# Crawler-fetched metadata served from a stable, unhashed URL: robots.txt, the
# sitemap, and llms.txt (the AI-agent discovery file). These can change on a
# redeploy, so they can't be immutable — but a one-day cache still spares the
# origin a re-fetch on every crawl while letting a redeploy propagate within 24h.
/robots.txt
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
/sitemap.xml
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
/llms.txt
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
